00:23:36,132 --> 00:23:38,972
<i>♪ When I'm ready,
rocking steady for my fans ♪</i>

236
00:23:39,052 --> 00:23:40,452
Where my ladies at?

237
00:23:41,532 --> 00:23:44,732
- Yo! Good show.
- Yeah, that's a good show, brother.

238
00:23:44,812 --> 00:23:47,132
- I'm feeling my shit.
- You want some of that?

239
00:23:47,212 --> 00:23:49,212
- What you smoking?
- Good shit, boy.

240
00:23:50,092 --> 00:23:50,972
A'ight.

241
00:23:51,972 --> 00:23:53,532
Damn!

242
00:23:54,452 --> 00:23:56,292
Eyes on, eyes on, eyes on.

243
00:23:57,612 --> 00:23:59,532
Don't stress. It's legal here.

244
00:23:59,612 --> 00:24:03,492
Pfft! Keep forgetting.
Welcome to Europe, I guess.

245
00:24:04,452 --> 00:24:06,852
- Kinda takes the joy out of it.
- Tell me about it.

246
00:24:06,932 --> 00:24:10,572
Careful! You break it, you pay for it.

247
00:24:12,012 --> 00:24:14,092
Always doing some bullshit.

248
00:24:14,172 --> 00:24:16,412
Tusk? Tusk?

249
00:24:18,612 --> 00:24:20,772
Yo, yo! We need some help over here!

250
00:24:25,052 --> 00:24:29,492
- I got you.
- Get it out! Get it out! Get it out!

251
00:24:29,572 --> 00:24:30,932
Call an ambulance!

252
00:25:21,612 --> 00:25:24,052
Commencing.

253
00:27:07,212 --> 00:27:09,212
- Did he say what it is?
- Nope.

254
00:27:20,932 --> 00:27:22,452
- Good morning.
- Morning.

255
00:27:31,532 --> 00:27:32,892
She's in here.

256
00:27:34,012 --> 00:27:36,452
So I go in,

257
00:27:36,532 --> 00:27:38,492
and there's not just the wound
from the glass.

258
00:27:38,572 --> 00:27:42,852
There's a hole. Dug in.
A bore hole, like a tiny tunnel.

259
00:27:42,932 --> 00:27:45,652
So I follow it, you know,
how deep does it go?

260
00:27:45,732 --> 00:27:48,932
It goes all the way from her ear canal
to deep in her brain.

261
00:27:49,612 --> 00:27:53,772
Where I find this.

262
00:27:53,852 --> 00:27:56,612
Nestled right in there. Looks quite cosy.

263
00:27:57,572 --> 00:28:00,612
- It's one of those bee things.
- An ADI.

264
00:28:01,412 --> 00:28:04,572
An Autonomous Drone Insect
from the Granular Project.

265
00:28:05,452 --> 00:28:08,012
- How did it get in there?
- I'd say it burrowed in.

266
00:28:09,412 --> 00:28:12,892
- Fuck me.
- That's not the worst part.

267
00:28:12,972 --> 00:28:15,572
It crawled right through
her dorsal posterior insula,

268
00:28:15,652 --> 00:28:18,532
which is basically
the brain's pain centre.

269
00:28:19,652 --> 00:28:21,452
You're talking agony off the scale.

270
00:28:22,532 --> 00:28:26,932
- You'd do anything to make it stop.
- Even cut your own throat.

271
00:28:43,812 --> 00:28:45,892
- Good afternoon.
- DCI Parke.

272
00:28:45,972 --> 00:28:48,492
- TDC Blue Colson.
- Okay. Thank you.

273
00:29:16,492 --> 00:29:19,092
They're so fucking fancy-looking,
these companies.

274
00:29:19,172 --> 00:29:21,852
- Billions on branding.
- Well, they can afford it.

275
00:29:21,932 --> 00:29:24,652
The whole ADI project's pretty much
bankrolled by the government.

276
00:29:24,732 --> 00:29:26,732
It's why so many people
are paranoid about it.

277
00:29:26,812 --> 00:29:30,332
Let me guess,
this is some people on the Internet?

278
00:29:31,012 --> 00:29:33,492
They reckon the government
uses the bees to spy on us.

279
00:29:34,412 --> 00:29:36,812
There's a schizophrenic world view.

280
00:29:50,852 --> 00:29:54,972
Jesus, I didn't expect to find myself
living in the future,

281
00:29:55,052 --> 00:29:56,372
but here I fucking well am.

282
00:29:59,252 --> 00:30:01,452
- Karin Parke?
- Uh-huh.

283
00:30:01,532 --> 00:30:02,732
Vanessa Dahl.

284
00:30:04,812 --> 00:30:06,732
Please. Follow me.

285
00:30:16,692 --> 00:30:19,772
You're after information
on our Project Swarm ADIs?

286
00:30:19,892 --> 00:30:21,492
That's right.

287
00:30:22,812 --> 00:30:24,092
Any particular reason?

288
00:30:24,692 --> 00:30:25,972
Yes.

289
00:30:46,532 --> 00:30:47,532
Rasmus.

290
00:30:50,692 --> 00:30:52,172
Rasmus Sjoberg.

291
00:30:52,252 --> 00:30:54,172
- He heads Swarm.
- Nice to meet you.

292
00:30:54,252 --> 00:30:56,332
- Hi.
- Hi.

293
00:30:56,412 --> 00:30:59,772
- Nice greenhouse.
- Yeah.

294
00:31:03,012 --> 00:31:06,292
So, your bees, your ADIs,
talk me through them.

295
00:31:06,372 --> 00:31:10,092
Colony Collapse Disorder.
We still don't know what's behind it.

296
00:31:10,172 --> 00:31:13,092
Bees themselves were virtually extinct

297
00:31:13,172 --> 00:31:17,292
so what our ADIs do
is effectively stand in for them.

298
00:31:17,372 --> 00:31:20,492
They're solar powered.
They don't need nectar.

299
00:31:20,572 --> 00:31:22,372
but they pollinate flowers the same way.

300
00:31:22,452 --> 00:31:25,492
They crawl inside,
pollen sticks to their legs

301
00:31:25,572 --> 00:31:27,612
and gets brushed off
the next flower they visit.

302
00:31:27,692 --> 00:31:30,172
- Can they make honey?
- Uh... No.

303
00:31:30,252 --> 00:31:31,972
I was joking.

304
00:31:34,092 --> 00:31:38,092
How do they know
where the flowers even are? I mean...

305
00:31:38,172 --> 00:31:39,452
Well, they have a sensor.

306
00:31:40,452 --> 00:31:42,612
Like a... camera?

307
00:31:42,692 --> 00:31:45,452
No. Just a basic visual sensor.

308
00:31:45,532 --> 00:31:48,052
You see,
they need rudimentary pattern recognition

309
00:31:48,132 --> 00:31:50,972
in order to locate compatible flora
and navigate.

310
00:31:51,052 --> 00:31:53,052
- <i>They</i> navigate?
- Yes.

311
00:31:53,132 --> 00:31:56,772
You don't... I don't know... steer them?

312
00:31:56,852 --> 00:31:59,412
They're autonomous.
That's right, isn't it?

313
00:31:59,492 --> 00:32:01,252
They make their own decisions.
They look after themselves.

314
00:32:01,332 --> 00:32:04,412
Yes. You see, the ADIs
cover the whole of the UK.

315
00:32:04,492 --> 00:32:07,092
We couldn't command each one
individually ourselves.

316
00:32:07,172 --> 00:32:08,772
It's just not logistically possible.

317
00:32:08,852 --> 00:32:12,812
No. We simply
set the behaviour and leave them to it.

318
00:32:12,892 --> 00:32:15,812
They even construct these hives
themselves.

319
00:32:15,892 --> 00:32:17,052
They reproduce...

320
00:32:17,132 --> 00:32:21,772
- They reproduce?
- Yes. Each hive is a replication point.

321
00:32:21,852 --> 00:32:24,132
- It's like a 3D printer, basically.
- Exactly.

322
00:32:24,212 --> 00:32:26,372
They create duplicates of themselves,

323
00:32:26,452 --> 00:32:29,412
create more hives
and spread out exponentially.

324
00:32:29,492 --> 00:32:32,052
- Cover the country.
- Maybe you should work here.

325
00:32:32,652 --> 00:32:35,932
Yeah, well, I read up on it.
It's impressive.

326
00:32:36,012 --> 00:32:39,652
It is. It's just a shame it's necessary.

327
00:32:39,732 --> 00:32:42,332
The alternative would have been
environmental catastrophe.

328
00:32:43,012 --> 00:32:44,092
Bees were dying out.

329
00:32:45,852 --> 00:32:48,492
So, what is it that brings you here?

330
00:32:50,252 --> 00:32:54,892
We think one of your ADIs
may be involved in an unexplained death.

331
00:32:54,972 --> 00:32:56,932
Sorry? A death?

332
00:32:57,012 --> 00:32:58,292
Uh-huh.

333
00:33:11,612 --> 00:33:12,852
Thank you.

334
00:33:27,372 --> 00:33:32,932
Yeah. It's one of ours.
But, look, these are not designed to...

335
00:33:33,012 --> 00:33:37,332
Kill people? I'd hope not.
Could it have malfunctioned somehow?

336
00:33:38,212 --> 00:33:42,212
No. I mean, when they do malfunction...

337
00:33:42,292 --> 00:33:45,652
It happens, but then they just break,
they just hit the ground.

338
00:33:46,732 --> 00:33:49,532
What if someone hacked one and then
they found a way of controlling it?

339
00:33:49,612 --> 00:33:50,892
That's impossible.

340
00:33:50,972 --> 00:33:53,492
You see,
it's got military-grade encryption,

341
00:33:53,572 --> 00:33:57,092
and you would need a diagnostic
controller, which is also encrypted.

342
00:33:57,172 --> 00:33:58,892
So I would say the likelihood is...

343
00:33:58,972 --> 00:34:02,292
I don't know what he's saying,
but it's not the same as "impossible."

344
00:34:09,972 --> 00:34:12,732
This is every hive we have online.

345
00:34:14,932 --> 00:34:16,052
See...

346
00:34:17,132 --> 00:34:21,092
These are the hives in the building here.

347
00:34:22,052 --> 00:34:25,852
- How many bees per hive?
- Around 4,000.

348
00:34:25,932 --> 00:34:28,252
- It's like air traffic control.
- Yeah.

349
00:34:28,332 --> 00:34:30,132
Is that the search input?

350
00:34:30,212 --> 00:34:33,252
- Yeah, but, uh... you'd need...
- Sorry.

351
00:34:36,612 --> 00:34:39,732
Jo Powers' postcode.

352
00:34:39,812 --> 00:34:41,492
Is that who this is about?

353
00:34:41,572 --> 00:34:44,412
- You said you get some malfunctions?
- A fair few, yes.

354
00:34:44,492 --> 00:34:47,532
They smack into a car or something.
We even had people trap them.

355
00:34:47,612 --> 00:34:50,732
You know, put them in the microwave
for YouTube videos.

356
00:34:50,812 --> 00:34:52,532
And this logs
any that drop off the system?

357
00:34:52,612 --> 00:34:53,652
Logs everything, yes.

358
00:34:53,732 --> 00:34:55,812
Did you lose any around here
on Monday evening?

359
00:34:55,892 --> 00:34:57,212
Well, I can check.

360
00:34:59,972 --> 00:35:05,532
Just one. Went out at 1903 hours.
Here, I can replay.

361
00:35:07,212 --> 00:35:08,372
There.

362
00:35:10,292 --> 00:35:13,412
- That's odd.
- What's odd?

363
00:35:13,492 --> 00:35:15,492
When they pass between hives,

364
00:35:15,572 --> 00:35:18,012
they switch from one jurisdiction
to another.

365
00:35:18,092 --> 00:35:22,132
- It's, you know, like a...
- It's like a phone between cell masts?

366
00:35:22,212 --> 00:35:26,772
Exactly. It tried to do that,
but there was nothing to switch to.

367
00:35:26,852 --> 00:35:31,612
Unless someone spoofed a hive and then
they've used that to commandeer your ADI.

368
00:35:31,692 --> 00:35:34,772
No, you would need
a diagnostic controller to do that.

369
00:35:34,852 --> 00:35:36,292
What's the range on one of those?

370
00:35:36,972 --> 00:35:39,372
Ten, 20 metres, perhaps.

371
00:35:40,492 --> 00:35:43,532
So whoever was controlling it would have
to be no more than 20 metres away.

372
00:35:43,612 --> 00:35:46,812
- Outside the house.
- Yeah. Sitting in a car, even.

373
00:35:46,892 --> 00:35:50,572
- Can you trace back who did this?
- Yes. I-I'm already trying to do that.

374
00:35:50,652 --> 00:35:51,652
Uh...

375
00:35:52,892 --> 00:35:58,012
You know what? Uh...
It would be easier without an audience.

376
00:36:02,092 --> 00:36:03,372
Okay.

377
00:36:03,452 --> 00:36:06,572
You two swap numbers,
keep a line of communication.

378
00:36:06,652 --> 00:36:10,892
Can you shut the whole thing down
if need be... hypothetically speaking?

379
00:36:10,972 --> 00:36:12,972
Even a short stoppage
would damage the ecosystem,

380
00:36:13,772 --> 00:36:16,892
and we'd need approval
from the Department of the Environment.

381
00:36:16,972 --> 00:36:20,612
We'll need a list of any Granular staff
that had access to that system,

382
00:36:20,692 --> 00:36:21,772
past or present.

383
00:36:21,852 --> 00:36:23,772
Some were government employees.

384
00:36:23,852 --> 00:36:26,412
Use a different font for those
if it helps.

385
00:36:29,372 --> 00:36:30,452
Bye.

386
00:36:59,212 --> 00:37:01,452
Nick, that's a set
of Granular personnel records.

387
00:37:01,532 --> 00:37:02,932
Root out anyone interesting.

388
00:37:03,012 --> 00:37:04,732
Maybe not just one.
Could be a group involved.

389
00:37:04,812 --> 00:37:06,532
Technically we should refer this up
to the NCA,

390
00:37:06,612 --> 00:37:08,972
but there's no fucking way
they're taking this off me.

391
00:37:09,052 --> 00:37:10,412
The NCA already knows about it.

392
00:37:12,052 --> 00:37:13,092
What?

393
00:37:14,772 --> 00:37:16,452
DCI Karin Parke?

394
00:37:18,732 --> 00:37:21,332
- Yes.
- Shaun Li, National Crime Agency.

395
00:37:22,292 --> 00:37:23,652
How come you're here?

396
00:37:24,772 --> 00:37:26,252
There's been more than one.

397
00:37:40,932 --> 00:37:42,932
This is Tusk, last night.

398
00:37:43,012 --> 00:37:45,412
- Shit.
- They thought it was a fit.

399
00:37:45,492 --> 00:37:46,572
Took him to the hospital.

400
00:37:46,652 --> 00:37:49,452
He had to be anaesthetised
to stop him mutilating himself.

401
00:37:50,372 --> 00:37:53,972
X-ray seemed to indicate some kind
of plaque or tumour in his brain

402
00:37:54,052 --> 00:37:56,732
so they popped him in the MRI.

403
00:37:56,812 --> 00:38:00,532
Yeah. Basically one big magnet.

404
00:38:00,612 --> 00:38:03,772
Tore it right out of his head,
through the eye socket.

405
00:38:05,692 --> 00:38:07,892
Battered the ADI too.

406
00:38:08,852 --> 00:38:12,172
Yours is more intact
so I'm gonna need it for analysis.

407
00:38:12,252 --> 00:38:13,772
It's evidence.

408
00:38:13,852 --> 00:38:17,252
Two's a pattern. It knocks
any malfunction theory in the head.

409
00:38:17,332 --> 00:38:20,332
- And they're similar victims.
- Similar?

410
00:38:20,412 --> 00:38:22,732
Both in the middle of online shit storms.

411
00:38:23,452 --> 00:38:26,172
Well, if you wanna kill someone,
there's a million easier ways to do it.

412
00:38:26,252 --> 00:38:29,332
Pull this off and you've done it
from across the street.

413
00:38:30,172 --> 00:38:33,892
No fingerprints, no DNA.
It's like wishing them dead.

414
00:38:43,652 --> 00:38:44,692
Fuck.

415
00:38:53,252 --> 00:38:54,372
Fuck.

416
00:38:58,172 --> 00:39:01,532
Guys? Come here.

417
00:39:12,612 --> 00:39:15,852
Okay, so, um... Jo Powers and Tusk,

418
00:39:15,932 --> 00:39:18,252
both were being kicked around
the Internet for hours,

419
00:39:18,332 --> 00:39:21,892
but in both their cases,
people were also tweeting their photos

420
00:39:21,972 --> 00:39:24,572
#DeathTo.

421
00:39:25,692 --> 00:39:27,092
- Like our friend the teacher.
- Right.

422
00:39:27,172 --> 00:39:30,932
She didn't know where she'd first heard
of it, but trace it back,

423
00:39:31,012 --> 00:39:34,692
and it looks like the first real use
of the hashtag was last weekend.

424
00:39:34,772 --> 00:39:36,812
- By who?
- Uh...

425
00:39:36,892 --> 00:39:38,612
Looks like, um...

426
00:39:39,572 --> 00:39:42,772
Looks like identical tweets
from a set of duplicate bot accounts.

427
00:39:44,372 --> 00:39:45,772
Um...

428
00:39:45,852 --> 00:39:49,252
Automated. It's like spam.

429
00:39:49,332 --> 00:39:52,932
This is someone trying to seed the tag,
you know? Get it out there.

430
00:39:53,012 --> 00:39:56,852
It's like bait. This is someone
wanting people to pick up on it.

431
00:39:57,652 --> 00:39:59,852
Check out the senders' avatar photos.

432
00:40:02,012 --> 00:40:03,572
Bees. Shit.

433
00:40:03,652 --> 00:40:05,252
Okay.

434
00:40:06,332 --> 00:40:07,492
There's more.

435
00:40:08,572 --> 00:40:12,252
So each tweet had a sort of
instruction video attached to it.

436
00:40:12,332 --> 00:40:13,652
- Uh-huh.
- There.

437
00:40:13,732 --> 00:40:16,012
"Game of Consequences"?

438
00:40:16,092 --> 00:40:18,292
It's like an unpopularity contest.

439
00:40:18,372 --> 00:40:21,692
Pick someone you don't like and if enough
other people choose the same name,

440
00:40:21,772 --> 00:40:23,732
then that's who gets targeted.

441
00:40:25,092 --> 00:40:27,092
Here, watch.

442
00:40:27,172 --> 00:40:29,252
<i>Game of Consequences.</i>

443
00:40:30,732 --> 00:40:33,932
<i>- Pick a target.</i>
- Oh, my God.

444
00:40:34,012 --> 00:40:38,212
<i>Post their name and photo
with #DeathTo.</i>

445
00:40:38,292 --> 00:40:39,292
No.

446
00:40:39,372 --> 00:40:45,132
<i>Most popular target
will be eliminated after 5 p.m. each day.</i>

447
00:40:45,212 --> 00:40:48,172
<i>Game resets at midnight.</i>

448
00:40:48,252 --> 00:40:50,092
- Oh, no.
- Fuck.

449
00:40:51,812 --> 00:40:56,092
Someone's holding a public ballot,
bumping off the top person.

450
00:40:57,012 --> 00:41:01,772
- Jesus, it's just mad.
- Yeah, and it's growing.

451
00:41:04,532 --> 00:41:08,732
Day one. 63 people used the hashtag
on Jo Powers, okay?

452
00:41:08,812 --> 00:41:13,132
On day two, 223 used it on Tusk.

453
00:41:13,212 --> 00:41:18,132
- Who's using it now?
- There's... There's loads more people.

454
00:41:18,212 --> 00:41:20,172
There's quite a few votes
for the Chancellor.

455
00:41:20,252 --> 00:41:22,012
- Yeah.
- Um...

456
00:41:22,092 --> 00:41:23,852
But at number one...

457
00:41:23,932 --> 00:41:29,372
is 880 people using it
on someone called Clara Meades.

458
00:41:29,452 --> 00:41:32,532
- Who's she?
- Clara Meades.

459
00:41:32,612 --> 00:41:35,492
Okay, um...
it looks like she was at a demo,

460
00:41:35,572 --> 00:41:38,252
and she took a selfie
in front of a war memorial.

461
00:41:39,452 --> 00:41:42,572
- Pretending to piss on it.
- Nice work, Clara.

462
00:41:42,652 --> 00:41:44,052
Yeah, it's getting near the end
of the vote,

463
00:41:44,132 --> 00:41:45,892
and her mentions are blowing up.

464
00:41:45,972 --> 00:41:49,012
- Tusk isn't public knowledge yet?
- Um, no.

465
00:41:49,092 --> 00:41:53,052
So people can't know the hashtag works.
They're using it to scare her.

466
00:41:53,132 --> 00:41:56,732
- Yeah, but they're gonna get her killed.
- We need to get to her before five.

467
00:41:56,812 --> 00:41:58,852
Yeah. Pulling her citizens details.

468
00:42:00,492 --> 00:42:02,252
You're not supposed
to have access to that.

469
00:42:02,332 --> 00:42:05,012
Yeah, I know. Just getting her location.

470
00:42:07,092 --> 00:42:08,092
There.

471
00:42:43,692 --> 00:42:44,972
Hello?

472
00:42:48,572 --> 00:42:52,372
Yeah, she is.
All right, all right, hold on.

473
00:42:52,452 --> 00:42:53,252
Clara!

474
00:42:56,172 --> 00:43:01,092
Police. For you.
How did they get my number?

475
00:43:02,692 --> 00:43:04,852
- Hello?
- Clara Meades?

476
00:43:04,932 --> 00:43:06,452
This is DCI Karin Parke, Met Police.

477
